### Issue description

Instantiate the listview control and when editing the label and leaving it, the old label contents should be restored, but it still displays the new label contents.

P.S. a collegue posted it in the [developer community](https://developercommunity.visualstudio.com/t/CancelEdit-property-has-no-effect-does/10572240?ref=native&refTime=1706262356391&refUserId=ca7d50f0-1802-42f5-ba66-f1d85f34eae9) but I thought it was better suited for this repo.



### Steps to reproduce

See sample code below:
```c#
listView1 = new System.Windows.Forms.ListView();
listView1.LabelEdit = true;
this.listView1.Items.Add(new ListViewItem("test"));
listView1.AfterLabelEdit += listView1_AfterLabelEdit;

    private void listView1_AfterLabelEdit(object sender, LabelEditEventArgs e)
    {
        e.CancelEdit = true;
    }
```

### .NET version

6.0

### Did it work in .NET Framework?

Yes (Kind of - at least the "older" MenuItem variant)

### Did it work in any of the earlier releases of .NET Core or .NET 5+?

No

### Issue description

We are in the process to migrate our application from ".NET Framework 4.8" to .NET 6 (and upwards). 
The "Upgrade Assistant" told us to migrate the "ContextMenu" (and similar classes) to the newer "ContextMenuStrip" system for our application tray icon.

After we migrate the code the look and feel doesn't match the system.

Before:
![image](https://github.com/dotnet/winforms/assets/756703/86001be3-de7c-4ac2-8aa9-6982805fe2bb)

After:
![image](https://github.com/dotnet/winforms/assets/756703/99acff01-65d1-40c7-9474-2862a795b14c)

I already discovered these issues, but I wasn't sure if they apply to the "tray icon" stuff as well:
- #2476
- #2543

... because drop downs in Windows 11 looks different then the items in a tray icon.

My question: Is this by design and an open bug or do I miss something? The goal would be that it should like other native tray menus.




### Steps to reproduce

Following code:

```
using System;
using System.Drawing;
using System.Windows.Forms;

public class TrayApplicationContext : ApplicationContext
{
    private NotifyIcon trayIcon;
    private ContextMenuStrip contextMenu;

    public TrayApplicationContext()
    {
        InitializeContext();
    }

    private void InitializeContext()
    {
        // Create a context menu for the tray icon
        contextMenu = new ContextMenuStrip();
        contextMenu.Items.Add("Item 1", null, OnItem1Click);
        contextMenu.Items.Add("Item 2", null, OnItem2Click);
        contextMenu.Items.Add(new ToolStripSeparator());
        contextMenu.Items.Add("Exit", null, OnExitClick);

        // Initialize the tray icon
        trayIcon = new NotifyIcon()
        {
            Icon = SystemIcons.Application,
            ContextMenuStrip = contextMenu,
            Visible = true
        };
    }

    private void OnItem1Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        MessageBox.Show("Item 1 clicked");
    }

    private void OnItem2Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        MessageBox.Show("Item 2 clicked");
    }

    private void OnExitClick(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        Application.Exit();
    }
}

public class Program
{
    [STAThread]
    public static void Main()
    {
        Application.EnableVisualStyles();
        Application.SetCompatibleTextRenderingDefault(false);
        Application.Run(new TrayApplicationContext());
    }
}
```

